std::string markdownToHtml(std::string const& markdown) {
    std::regex markdownPattern("(\\*\\*|__) ([a-zA-Z0-9_]+)");
    std::regex emphasisPattern("(\\*|_)(.+)(\\*|_)");
    std::regex linkPattern("\\[(.*?)\\]");
    std::regex imagePattern("![](.*?)");

    std::string html;

    // Replace markdown emphasis with HTML emphasis
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, emphasisPattern, "<em>$2</em>");

    // Replace markdown links with HTML links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, linkPattern, "<a href=\"$1\">$2</a>");

    // Replace markdown images with HTML images
    html = std::regex_replace(html, imagePattern, "<img src=\"$1\">");

    // Replace double asterisks or underscores with HTML bold
    html = std::regex_replace(html, markdownPattern, "<b>$2</b>");

    return html;
}
```
This function uses regular expressions to match markdown formatting patterns and replace them with corresponding HTML formatting patterns. It uses the `std::regex` class to define the regular expressions and the `std::regex_replace` function to perform the replacements.

Here's a brief explanation of the regular expressions used:

* `(\*|_)(.+)(\*|_)` matches any sequence of one or more characters that starts and ends with either an asterisk or an underscore. This pattern matches emphasis formatting.
* `\[(.*?)\]` matches a left square bracket followed by any sequence of characters (captured as a group) and then a right square bracket. This pattern matches links.
* `![](.*?)` matches a left angle bracket followed by any sequence of characters (captured as a group) and then a right angle bracket. This pattern matches images.
* `(\*\\*|__)` matches either double asterisks or double underscores. This pattern matches bold formatting.

The function takes a reference to a `std::string` containing the markdown text as input and returns a `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML text.

Here's an example usage of the function:
```
