```
Next, you'll need to add the `tableofcontents` environment to the document where you want the table of contents to appear. For example, you might add it after the introduction section:
```
\section{Introduction}
\label{introduction}

\tableofcontents
```
The `tableofcontents` environment will automatically generate a table of contents based on the section headings in your document. By default, it will include all section headings up to the current section, so in this example, it will include the `Introduction` section and any sections that come after it.

If you want to customize the table of contents, you can use the `tableofcontents` environment's options. For example, you can specify the format of the table of contents using the `format` option:
```
\tableofcontents(format=plain)
```
This will generate a plain table of contents with no frills. You can also use the `parts` option to include part headings in the table of contents:
```
\tableofcontents(parts)
```
This will include part headings in the table of contents, in addition to section headings.

Finally, you can use the `secnumdepth` option to specify the depth of the table of contents. For example, to include only sections and subsections, but not subsubsections, you can use:
```
